    "text": "The DialTimeout configuration chain spans two repositories and multiple layers.\n\n## Kubernetes apiserver (kubernetes/kubernetes under staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/)\n\n**staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/storagebackend/factory/etcd3.go** is the primary consumer-side file. It defines a package-level constant `dialTimeout = 20 * time.Second` (with a comment explaining it must be at least 20s to avoid TLS failures on heavily loaded arm64 CPUs, referencing issue #64649). This value is then passed directly as `DialTimeout: dialTimeout` when constructing a `clientv3.Config` struct to create the etcd v3 client used by the Kubernetes storage backend.\n\n**staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/etcd3/preflight/checks.go** uses the Go standard library `net.DialTimeout` function to perform a preflight connectivity check against the etcd endpoint before the storage backend is fully initialized. This is a dial timeout applied at the TCP level to verify etcd is reachable.\n\n**staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/etcd3/testserver/test_server.go** (not a `_test.go` file \u2014 it is a reusable test server helper package) sets `DialTimeout: 10 * time.Second` in a `clientv3.Config` when creating an etcd client connected to the embedded test server.\n\n## etcd client library (etcd-io/etcd under client/)\n\n**client/v3/config.go** is the authoritative definition: it declares `DialTimeout time.Duration` as a field of the `Config` struct (JSON tag `dial-timeout`), with the doc comment: \"DialTimeout is the timeout for failing to establish a connection.\"\n\n**client/v3/client.go** is where `DialTimeout` is actually applied at runtime. When `NewClient` dials the gRPC connection, it checks `c.cfg.DialTimeout > 0` and wraps the dial context with `context.WithTimeout(c.ctx, c.cfg.DialTimeout)` in three separate code paths (initial dial, auto-sync, and reconnect). This is the mechanism that enforces the timeout.\n\n**client/v3/lease.go** uses `c.cfg.DialTimeout` to compute the keepalive timeout for the lease client: `NewLeaseFromLeaseClient(..., c.cfg.DialTimeout+time.Second)`.\n\n**client/v3/maintenance.go** uses `c.cfg.DialTimeout` to set a context deadline for defragmentation and other maintenance operations.\n\n**client/pkg/transport/transport.go** provides `NewTransport(info TLSInfo, dialtimeoutd time.Duration)` which sets the `net.Dialer.Timeout` field to `dialtimeoutd`, applying the dial timeout at the HTTP/TCP transport layer.\n\n**client/pkg/transport/timeout_transport.go** provides `NewTimeoutTransport(info TLSInfo, dialtimeoutd, rdtimeoutd, wtimeoutd time.Duration)` which calls `NewTransport` with the dial timeout and additionally configures a custom `net.Dialer` with the same timeout.\n\n## etcd server (etcd-io/etcd under server/)\n\n**server/config/config.go** defines the `PeerDialTimeout()` method on `ServerConfig`, which computes the dial timeout for peer-to-peer raft communication (1s for queue wait plus the election timeout).\n\n**server/etcdserver/server.go** calls `cfg.PeerDialTimeout()` in two places: once to create a `rafthttp.NewRoundTripper` for the pipeline transport, and once to set `DialTimeout: cfg.PeerDialTimeout()` in the `rafthttp.Transport` struct used for raft peer communication.\n\n**server/etcdserver/api/rafthttp/transport.go** defines the `Transport` struct with a `DialTimeout time.Duration` field (\"maximum duration before timing out dial of the request\"). In its `Start()` method it passes `t.DialTimeout` to both `newStreamRoundTripper` and `NewRoundTripper`.\n\n**server/etcdserver/api/rafthttp/util.go** provides `NewRoundTripper(tlsInfo, dialTimeout)` and `newStreamRoundTripper(tlsInfo, dialTimeout)`, both of which call `transport.NewTimeoutTransport` with the `dialTimeout` parameter, bridging the rafthttp layer to the client transport layer.\n\n**server/etcdmain/grpc_proxy.go** configures the etcd gRPC proxy by creating two `clientv3.Config` structs, each with `DialTimeout: 5 * time.Second`, for connecting to the upstream etcd cluster.\n\n**server/etcdmain/config.go** defines `ProxyDialTimeoutMs uint` (default 1000ms) as part of the proxy configuration struct, exposed as the `--proxy-dial-timeout` CLI flag.\n\n**server/etcdmain/etcd.go** converts `ProxyDialTimeoutMs` to a `time.Duration` and passes it as the `dialtimeoutd` argument to `transport.NewTimeoutTransport` (via `NewRoundTripper`) for both client-facing and peer-facing proxy transports.\n\n## Summary of the DialTimeout chain\n\nThe `DialTimeout` / `dialTimeout` timeout flows as follows:\n1. **Kubernetes apiserver** hardcodes `dialTimeout = 20 * time.Second` in `factory/etcd3.go` and passes it as `clientv3.Config.DialTimeout` when creating the etcd storage client.\n2. **etcd client library** (`client/v3/config.go`) defines the `DialTimeout` field; `client/v3/client.go` enforces it by wrapping the gRPC dial context with `context.WithTimeout`; `lease.go` and `maintenance.go` also use it for operation timeouts.\n3. **etcd transport layer** (`client/pkg/transport/transport.go`, `timeout_transport.go`) applies the dial timeout to the underlying `net.Dialer.Timeout`.\n4. **etcd server peer transport** (`server/config/config.go` \u2192 `server/etcdserver/server.go` \u2192 `server/etcdserver/api/rafthttp/transport.go` \u2192 `server/etcdserver/api/rafthttp/util.go`) propagates `PeerDialTimeout()` through the rafthttp `Transport.DialTimeout` field down to `NewTimeoutTransport`.\n5. **etcd gRPC proxy** (`server/etcdmain/grpc_proxy.go`) sets its own `DialTimeout: 5 * time.Second` when connecting to upstream etcd.\n6. **etcd legacy proxy** (`server/etcdmain/config.go`, `server/etcdmain/etcd.go`) uses `ProxyDialTimeoutMs` (default 1000ms) for HTTP proxy transports."
